content.problemStatement:
The `if-else if` structure in Java is an extension of the basic `if-else` statement that allows us to check multiple conditions sequentially. This structure is useful when we need to evaluate different conditions and execute specific blocks of code based on the first matching condition.

**Syntax:**
```java
if (condition1) {
    // Code to execute if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // Code to execute if condition2 is true
} else {
    // Code to execute if none of the above conditions are true
}
```

---

**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Initialize the variable
        int number = 25;  'number' 

        // Check if the number is greater than 0
        if (number > 0) {
            System.out.println("The number is positive.");
        } 
        // Check if the number is less than 0
        else if (number < 0) {
            System.out.println("The number is negative.");
        } 
        // If the number is neither positive nor negative (i.e., it is 0)
        else {
            System.out.println("The number is zero."); 
        }
    }
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```default
The number is positive.
```

